    • Class dev.gruncan.spotify.webapi.objects.albums.SimplifiedAlbum

      class SimplifiedAlbum extends Object implements Serializable

      • Serialized Fields

        • albumType
          String albumType
          The type of the album.
        • copyrights
          SpotifyCopyright[] copyrights
          The copyright statements of the album.
        • externalIDS
          SpotifyExternalID externalIDS
          Known external IDs for the album.
        • externalUrls
          String externalUrls
          Known external URLs for this album.
          The Spotify URL for the object.
        • genres
          String[] genres
          A list of the genres the album is associated with. If not yet classified, the array is empty.
        • href
          String href
          A link to the Web API endpoint providing full details of the album.
        • id
          String id
          The Spotify ID for the album.
        • images
          SpotifyImage[] images
          The cover art for the album in various sizes, widest first.
        • label
          String label
          The label associated with the album.
        • markets
          Country[] markets
          The markets in which the album is available: ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country codes. NOTE: an album is considered available in a market when at least 1 of its tracks is available in that market.
        • name
          String name
          The name of the album. In case of an album takedown, the value may be an empty string
        • popularity
          int popularity
          The popularity of the album. The value will be between 0 and 100, with 100 being the most popular.
        • releaseDate
          String releaseDate
          The date the album was first released.
        • releaseDatePrecision
          String releaseDatePrecision
          The precision with which release_date value is known.
        • restrictions
          String restrictions
          Included in the response when a content restriction is applied.
          The reason for the restriction. Albums may be restricted if the content is not available in a given market, to the user's subscription type, or when the user's account is set to not play explicit content. Additional reasons may be added in the future.
        • totalTracks
          int totalTracks
          The number of tracks in the album.
        • type
          String type
          The object type.
        • uri
          String uri
          The Spotify URI for the album.

    • Class dev.gruncan.spotify.webapi.objects.playlists.SimplifiedPlaylist

      class SimplifiedPlaylist extends Object implements Serializable

      • Serialized Fields

        • description
          String description
          The playlist description. Only returned for modified, verified playlists, otherwise null.
        • externalUrls
          String externalUrls
          Known external URLs for this playlist.
          Information about the followers of the playlist.
        • href
          String href
          A link to the Web API endpoint providing full details of the playlist.
        • id
          String id
          The Spotify ID for the playlist.
        • images
          SpotifyImage[] images
          Images for the playlist. The array may be empty or contain up to three images. The images are returned by size in descending order. See Working with Playlists. Note: If returned, the source URL for the image (url) is temporary and will expire in less than a day.
        • isCollaborative
          boolean isCollaborative
          true if the owner allows other users to modify the playlist.
        • isPublic
          boolean isPublic
          The playlist's public/private status: true the playlist is public, false the playlist is private, null the playlist status is not relevant.
        • name
          String name
          The name of the playlist.
        • owner
          PlaylistContributor owner
          The user who owns the playlist
        • snapshotID
          String snapshotID
          The version identifier for the current playlist. Can be supplied in other requests to target a specific playlist version
        • tracks
          PlaylistTracksSearch tracks
          The tracks of the playlist.
        • type
          String type
          The object type: "playlist"
        • uri
          String uri
          The Spotify URI for the playlist.

      class Track extends SimplifiedTrack implements Serializable

      • Serialized Fields

        • album
          TrackAlbum album
          The album on which the track appears. The album object includes a link in href to full information about the album
        • artists
          Artist[] artists
          The artists who performed the track. Each artist object includes a link in href to more detailed information about the artist.
        • externalIDs
          SpotifyExternalID externalIDs
          Known external IDs for the track.
        • popularity
          int popularity
          The popularity of the track. The value will be between 0 and 100, with 100 being the most popular. The popularity of a track is a value between 0 and 100, with 100 being the most popular. The popularity is calculated by algorithm and is based, in the most part, on the total number of plays the track has had and how recent those plays are. Generally speaking, songs that are being played a lot now will have a higher popularity than songs that were played a lot in the past. Duplicate tracks (e.g. the same track from a single and an album) are rated independently. Artist and album popularity is derived mathematically from track popularity. Note: the popularity value may lag actual popularity by a few days: the value is not updated in real time.

      class TrackAudioFeatures extends Object implements Serializable

      • Serialized Fields

        • acousticness
          double acousticness
          A confidence measure from 0.0 to 1.0 of whether the track is acoustic. 1.0 represents high confidence the track is acoustic.
        • analysisUrl
          String analysisUrl
          A URL to access the full audio analysis of this track. An access token is required to access this data.
        • danceability
          double danceability
          Danceability describes how suitable a track is for dancing based on a combination of musical elements including tempo, rhythm stability, beat strength, and overall regularity. A value of 0.0 is least danceable and 1.0 is most danceable.
        • duration
          int duration
          The duration of the track in milliseconds.
        • energy
          double energy
          Energy is a measure from 0.0 to 1.0 and represents a perceptual measure of intensity and activity. Typically, energetic tracks feel fast, loud, and noisy. For example, death metal has high energy, while a Bach prelude scores low on the scale. Perceptual features contributing to this attribute include dynamic range, perceived loudness, timbre, onset rate, and general entropy.
        • id
          String id
          The Spotify ID for the track.
        • instrumentalness
          double instrumentalness
          Predicts whether a track contains no vocals. "Ooh" and "aah" sounds are treated as instrumental in this context. Rap or spoken word tracks are clearly "vocal". The closer the instrumentalness value is to 1.0, the greater likelihood the track contains no vocal content. Values above 0.5 are intended to represent instrumental tracks, but confidence is higher as the value approaches 1.0.
        • key
          int key
          The key the track is in. Integers map to pitches using standard Pitch Class notation. E.g. 0 = C, 1 = C/D, 2 = D, and so on. If no key was detected, the value is -1.
        • liveness
          double liveness
          Detects the presence of an audience in the recording. Higher liveness values represent an increased probability that the track was performed live. A value above 0.8 provides strong likelihood that the track is live.
        • loudness
          double loudness
          The overall loudness of a track in decibels (dB). Loudness values are averaged across the entire track and are useful for comparing relative loudness of tracks. Loudness is the quality of a sound that is the primary psychological correlate of physical strength (amplitude). Values typically range between -60 and 0 db.
        • mode
          int mode
          Mode indicates the modality (major or minor) of a track, the type of scale from which its melodic content is derived. Major is represented by 1 and minor is 0
        • speechiness
          double speechiness
          Speechiness detects the presence of spoken words in a track. The more exclusively speech-like the recording (e.g. talk show, audio book, poetry), the closer to 1.0 the attribute value. Values above 0.66 describe tracks that are probably made entirely of spoken words. Values between 0.33 and 0.66 describe tracks that may contain both music and speech, either in sections or layered, including such cases as rap music. Values below 0.33 most likely represent music and other non-speech-like tracks.
        • tempo
          double tempo
          The overall estimated tempo of a track in beats per minute (BPM). In musical terminology, tempo is the speed or pace of a given piece and derives directly from the average beat duration.
        • timeSignature
          int timeSignature
          An estimated time signature. The time signature (meter) is a notational convention to specify how many beats are in each bar (or measure). The time signature ranges from 3 to 7 indicating time signatures of "3/4", to "7/4".
        • trackHref
          String trackHref
          A link to the Web API endpoint providing full details of the track
        • type
          String type
          The object type.
        • uri
          String uri
          The Spotify URI for the track.
        • valence
          double valence
          A measure from 0.0 to 1.0 describing the musical positiveness conveyed by a track. Tracks with high valence sound more positive (e.g. happy, cheerful, euphoric), while tracks with low valence sound more negative (e.g. sad, depressed, angry).

      class AudioSegment extends Object implements Serializable

      • Serialized Fields

        • confidence
          double confidence
          The confidence, from 0.0 to 1.0, of the reliability of the segmentation. Segments of the song which are difficult to logically segment (e.g: noise) may correspond to low values in this field.
        • duration
          double duration
          The duration (in seconds) of the segment.
        • loudnessEnd
          double loudnessEnd
          The offset loudness of the segment in decibels (dB). This value should be equivalent to the loudness_start of the following segment.
        • loudnessMax
          double loudnessMax
          The peak loudness of the segment in decibels (dB). Combined with loudness_start and loudness_max_time, these components can be used to describe the "attack" of the segment.
        • loudnessMaxTime
          double loudnessMaxTime
          The segment-relative offset of the segment peak loudness in seconds. Combined with loudness_start and loudness_max, these components can be used to desctibe the "attack" of the segment.
        • loudnessStart
          double loudnessStart
          The onset loudness of the segment in decibels (dB). Combined with loudness_max and loudness_max_time, these components can be used to describe the "attack" of the segment.
        • pitches
          Double[] pitches
          Pitch content is given by a "chroma" vector, corresponding to the 12 pitch classes C, C#, D to B, with values ranging from 0 to 1 that describe the relative dominance of every pitch in the chromatic scale. For example a C Major chord would likely be represented by large values of C, E and G (i.e. classes 0, 4, and 7).
          Vectors are normalized to 1 by their strongest dimension, therefore noisy sounds are likely represented by values that are all close to 1, while pure tones are described by one value at 1 (the pitch) and others near 0. As can be seen below, the 12 vector indices are a combination of low-power spectrum values at their respective pitch frequencies.
        • start
          double start
          The starting point (in seconds) of the segment.
        • timbre
          Double[] timbre
          Timbre is the quality of a musical note or sound that distinguishes different types of musical instruments, or voices. It is a complex notion also referred to as sound color, texture, or tone quality, and is derived from the shape of a segment's spectro-temporal surface, independently of pitch and loudness. The timbre feature is a vector that includes 12 unbounded values roughly centered around 0. Those values are high level abstractions of the spectral surface, ordered by degree of importance.
          For completeness however, the first dimension represents the average loudness of the segment; second emphasizes brightness; third is more closely correlated to the flatness of a sound; fourth to sounds with a stronger attack; etc. See an image below representing the 12 basis functions (i.e. template segments).
